East 38th Street, south side, west from First Ave. The gasoline station shown in the foreground, is at the S.W. corner of First Ave. Also shown is the Second Ave. Elevated Line.

October 12, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

E. 38th Street, west from First Avenue, showing mainly the southerly side of this thoroughfare. Running diagonally thru the corner property at the left are the tubes of the Queens Midtown tunnel. The former tenements standing at this site were demolished in 1929 to make way for a gasoline station and which in time was razed for the present improvement in April 1938. The adjoining buildings will follow in the Fall of 1939. To the right is the Eletco Co. warehouse, housing the delivery services of "United Parcels". This structure was erected in late 1928.

E. 38th Street, south side, west from (No. 316 left) a point between First and Second Avenue and to the latter. Note the political signs at the left indicating the Congressional 1938 struggle between incumbent John J. O'Connor and the successful candidate James H. Fay. This contest had national attention because of Administration interest. The name of Israel Amter indicates the Communist party's candidate for Governor of the State of New York.
